To master the full course of a Master of Divinity (MDiv), students typically study a structured syllabus covering biblical studies, theology, church history, pastoral ministry, biblical languages, and practical ministry skills, using a vast collection of foundational books and commentaries.[1][2][3][4][5]

### Core Areas and Essential Books

- **Biblical Studies**:
   - Strong’s Bible Concordance[6]
   - The New Unger’s Bible Dictionary[6]
   - Unger’s Bible Handbook[6]
   - Matthew Henry's Commentary[7]
   - Exposition Commentary by Warren W. Wiersbe[7]

- **Theology**:
   - Abstract of Systematic Theology by Boyce[6]
   - Basic Theology by Ryrie[6]
   - Christian Theology – An Introduction by Alister McGrath[6]
   - Essentials of Evangelical Theology by Bloesch[6]
   - Evangelical Dictionary of Theology by Ewell[6]
   - God, Revelation, and Authority by Carl F. H. Henry[6]
   - Systematic Theology by Wayne Grudem or Lewis Sperry Chafer (multi-volume)[7]

- **Biblical Languages**:
   - Word Studies in the Greek New Testament by Kenneth Wuest[7]
   - Word Pictures in the New Testament by A.T. Robertson[7]

- **Church History**:
   - The Westminster Confession of Faith[1]
   - Baptist History & Distinctive (regional adaptation)[4]
   - Our Reasonable Faith by Herman Bavinck[1]
   - On the Incarnation by Saint Athanasius[1]

- **Pastoral Ministry & Homiletics**:
   - Principles of Expository Preaching by Unger[6]
   - The Hermeneutical Spiral by Osborne[6]
   - The 12 Essential Skills for Great Preaching by McDill[6]
   - Not the Way It’s Supposed to Be: A Breviary of Sin by Cornelius Plantinga[1]

- **Practical Theology & Applied Subjects**:
   - The Doctrine of God by Gerald Bray[1]
   - Why I Am Not an Arminian by Williams & Peterson[1]
   - Studies in Church Planting, Growth, Leadership, and Counseling[4]

### Course Syllabus Structure (Typical Subjects)

- Introduction to Old Testament & New Testament
- Biblical Greek and Hebrew (preliminary and advanced)
- History of Christianity: Ancient, Medieval, Modern[2]
- Biblical Hermeneutics and Homiletics
- Pentateuch, Pauline Epistles, Synoptic Gospels, Gospel of John, Revelation[3][4]
- Systematic Theology I & II[4]
- Christian Ethics, Pastoral Care, Counseling, Leadership
- Discipleship, Missions, Evangelism, Comparative Religion
- Research Methodology and Thesis[2][4]

### Complementary Reading Lists

- *One Thing You Can’t Do in Heaven* by Mark Cahill[8]
- *Spiritual Discipleship* by J. Oswald Sanders[8]
- *The Case for Christ* by Lee Strobel[8]
- *Process Theology: An Introductory Exposition* by John B. Cobb Jr.[9]
- *Holy Envy: Finding God in the Faith of Others* by Barbara Brown Taylor[9]

### Notes
- Required books and syllabi may vary depending on denominational orientation and regional theological traditions.[3][2][4][1]
- Most seminaries require both regional and international works, as well as thesis writing and oral exams for graduation.[4]

This list outlines the key books and subjects typically covered in a comprehensive Master of Divinity course and can be built into a structured curriculum for advanced theological study.[2][4][1][6]

